@ededdellie the media kinda made how we view the migrants workers, especially in my dayz where i grew up listening to my mom saying, hei dont go out later you meet drunk indians and get into trouble. The news have also been focusing more on the indian troublemakers. Therefore it gave us the negative view of the whole ethnic group of being a drunk, rapist and domestic violence. @ziiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiii everywhere i go, i see us chinese. And we chinese, especially those who lived through 90s and 00s can really be bigots
Tbh why are we chinese being like this towards our migrants workers

While we live comfortably on our Aircon room and our comfortable bed, we should also gratitude the migrant workers who sacrifice their blood sweat and tears, to leave their family behind trying to make a living, these migrant workers are probably one of the money people to help build Singapore, buildings, HDB and more. I hope all the migrant workers out there can preserve during this covid situation.
@celine_lee.thium These can only be achieved via revolution. Without it, the government, allying with the companies and CEOs, will offer concession after concession to appease and delude the workers.

The truth is the world runs on money now. While the rest of us are put into good schools and jobs, others who dont have such experience get put into lower ranking jobs that no one else except them would want to take. No employer would want to pay large sums of money to people with no qualifications or help them provide good accommodation. People want the most profit and that's it. Changing this will take time and it's clear our voices are being heard. Hopefully things get better for migrant workers.

@jojo_ochaco government ownself check ownself, doesn't work. We need to force the minister to resign, or at least address this to them. If doesn't work, vote them out of power

Hope for change is not enough. MOM has turned a blind eye to these workers, and their mistreatment for so long. This was common knowledge, that we used to brush under the carpet. But now with the dormitories basically being hot-spots for COVID-19, the issue of worker rights has finally surfaced. Disgusting, cramped living conditions have finally been brought up. It is clear that MOM does not give two craps about these workers, that they claim to love so much. Change must be made. The reinforcement of these workers' rights as human beings must be made. And MOM needs to be punished for its negligence. Or else, I don't know how we can call ourselves human, if we can't stand up for our fellow humans.
